context: Shorter, black-and-white daily strips began to appear early in the 20th century, and became established in newspapers after the success in <a1_0><b6_0>1907<b6_0/><a1_0/> of Bud Fisher's <a0_0><b4_0><b5_0>Mutt and Jeff<b5_0/><b4_0/><a0_0/>. Humour strips predominated at first, and in the 1920s and <a2_0><b7_0>1930s<b7_0/><a2_0/> strips with continuing stories in genres such as adventure and drama also became popular. Thin periodicals called comic books appeared in the 1930s, at first reprinting newspaper comic strips; by the end of the decade, original content began to dominate. The success in 1938 of <a3_0><b8_0>Action Comics<b8_0/><a3_0/> and its lead hero Superman marked the beginning of the Golden Age of Comic Books, in which the superhero genre was prominent.
